This week we talked about the HER process of color. In the beginning of Friday’s lecture we discussed studies that showed red facilitates tasks with attention, detail, and focus and blue facilitates tasks with creativity. This immediately made me think of the lounges in Kay Hall. One lounge is painted red, while the lounge right next to it is painted blue. The color of the walls may dictate the tasks that would be completed most effectively in each room. Creative tasks, such as playing the piano, would be best done in the blue room. Attentive tasks, such as math or engineering homework, would be best done in the red room. #envpsy #envpsyw4

Everyone in my family is pretty short, my dad is only 5’6” and I am 5’1”, so we have our cabinets set up to be lower than what is standard to make our kitchen more useable. This is an example of person x environment interaction, which is defined by the APA as “the relationship between a person's psychological and physical capacities and the demands placed on those capacities by the person's social and physical environment.” The environmental design in my kitchen is tailored to my family so that less of a demand is placed on our physical capacity as short people. This is also a pretty clear example of biometrics. #envpsyw4

The design flaw of bunk beds in Cornell dorms is caused by the HER process biomechanics. Biomechanics relates to how the body interacts with a product or environment.As shown, the space between the second and third steps of the ladder is greater than that between all of the others. It presents an anthropometric issue by making the ladder more difficult for people with short legs to use. A consequence of this could be injury caused by slipping when climbing down the ladder.  #envpsy #envpsyw4
The chair in my dormitory is designed to fit our body better, and it illustrates the concept of anthropometrics. #envpsy #envpsyw4

She has a wrist band to restrain flexion and extension but I'm planning to buy her a wrist rest pad and mouse that is more ergonomic.

HER Process: Cognitive Ergonomics. Here is one of the light switches from the hallway on the second floor (living quarters) of the house I’m living in. You would think that the left-most switch would control the left-most light, the center switch the center light, etc. Unfortunately it’s not wired like that. The middle switch actually controls the left-most light while the left switch controls the middle light. This make it difficult to use; moreover, unless we consciously think really hard about the switch we need to flip, we end up instinctually reaching for the wrong one. 

#envpsy #envpsyw4
